title Cybersecurity Risk Management from the Executive's Point of View (May 2023)

// OWM coordinate convention: [visibility, maturity]
// visibility 0 = bottom of map (invisible infrastructure), 1 = top (user/anchor)
// maturity   0 = Genesis (far left), 1 = Commodity (far right)

// -------------------- Anchor --------------------
// Executives own cybersecurity risk at the top; their decisions are shaped
// by three drivers that sit just below them.
component Executives [0.97, 0.80]

// -------------------- Executive-level drivers --------------------
component P&L Impact [0.88, 0.90]
component Compliance Obligations [0.88, 0.82]
component Risk Appetite [0.88, 0.55]

// -------------------- Governance / Risk Posture layer --------------------
// What the executives sign off on to translate appetite into action.
component Mitigation/Transfer/Accept Mix [0.78, 0.60]
component Cyber Insurance [0.78, 0.75]
component Risk Register [0.72, 0.68]

// -------------------- Risk Assessment layer --------------------
component Risk Assessment Methodology [0.65, 0.55]
component Risk Identification Practice [0.65, 0.45]
component Asset Inventory [0.65, 0.72]

// -------------------- Frameworks --------------------
// Risk frameworks (NIST CSF, ISO 27005) sit below methodology.
// Compliance frameworks (ISO 27001, SOC 2, PCI DSS, GDPR) sit lower / further right
// because they are the most standardised.
component Risk Framework (NIST CSF / ISO 27005) [0.55, 0.72]
component Compliance Framework (ISO 27001 / SOC 2 / PCI / GDPR) [0.55, 0.85]

// -------------------- Risk Quantification --------------------
// Split by maturity: risk matrices are commoditised, likelihood/impact is productised,
// FAIR quantification is still bespoke/expert.
component Risk Matrices [0.48, 0.78]
component Likelihood/Impact Scoring [0.48, 0.62]
component FAIR Quantification [0.48, 0.32]

// -------------------- Operational Security --------------------
component Reporting to Board [0.60, 0.70]
component Incident Response [0.42, 0.78]
component Security Monitoring [0.38, 0.85]
component SOC Tooling (SIEM/XDR) [0.35, 0.72]
component Security Testing [0.42, 0.62]
component Pen Testing [0.32, 0.70]
component Bug Bounty [0.32, 0.55]

// -------------------- Emerging: LLM --------------------
// Two distinct roles. Defence = LLM-assisted SOC/analyst copilots (custom/emerging in May 2023).
// Risk  = LLM-as-attack-surface (prompt injection, data leakage) — genesis in May 2023.
component LLM-Assisted Defence [0.28, 0.20]
component LLM-as-Risk (prompt injection, data leakage) [0.55, 0.12]

// -------------------- Dependency Edges (a depends on b => visibility(a) >= visibility(b)) --------------------

// Executives depend on the three drivers and on their reporting channel
Executives->P&L Impact
Executives->Compliance Obligations
Executives->Risk Appetite
Executives->Reporting to Board

// P&L impact is what cyber insurance and the mitigation/transfer/accept mix pay down
P&L Impact->Cyber Insurance
P&L Impact->Mitigation/Transfer/Accept Mix

// Compliance obligations drive the compliance framework and the risk framework
Compliance Obligations->Compliance Framework (ISO 27001 / SOC 2 / PCI / GDPR)
Compliance Obligations->Risk Framework (NIST CSF / ISO 27005)

// Risk appetite drives the register and the mitigation/transfer/accept mix
Risk Appetite->Risk Register
Risk Appetite->Mitigation/Transfer/Accept Mix

// The posture layer depends on assessment
Mitigation/Transfer/Accept Mix->Risk Assessment Methodology
Cyber Insurance->Risk Assessment Methodology
Cyber Insurance->Risk Register
Risk Register->Risk Assessment Methodology
Risk Register->Asset Inventory

// Assessment needs identification and inventory, and methodology needs frameworks/quantification
Risk Assessment Methodology->Risk Identification Practice
Risk Assessment Methodology->Asset Inventory
Risk Assessment Methodology->Risk Framework (NIST CSF / ISO 27005)
Risk Assessment Methodology->Likelihood/Impact Scoring
Risk Assessment Methodology->FAIR Quantification
Risk Assessment Methodology->Risk Matrices
Risk Identification Practice->Asset Inventory

// Reporting to board pulls data from monitoring and from the register
Reporting to Board->Security Monitoring
Reporting to Board->Risk Register

// Operational stack dependencies
Security Monitoring->SOC Tooling (SIEM/XDR)
Incident Response->Security Monitoring
Incident Response->SOC Tooling (SIEM/XDR)
Security Testing->Pen Testing
Security Testing->Bug Bounty
Risk Identification Practice->Security Testing
Risk Identification Practice->Security Monitoring

// LLM angle
LLM-Assisted Defence->SOC Tooling (SIEM/XDR)
LLM-Assisted Defence->Security Monitoring
// LLM-as-Risk is itself a risk the register must track — sits to the left (genesis) but hooks into the register
Risk Identification Practice->LLM-as-Risk (prompt injection, data leakage)
Risk Register->LLM-as-Risk (prompt injection, data leakage)

// -------------------- Movement (evolution direction) --------------------

// Compliance frameworks are slowly drifting right (more commoditised via SOC 2 / GDPR tooling)
evolve Compliance Framework (ISO 27001 / SOC 2 / PCI / GDPR) 0.92

// Risk framework drifts right as NIST CSF 2.0 is being drafted in 2023
evolve Risk Framework (NIST CSF / ISO 27005) 0.80

// Cyber insurance is productising further after the 2021-22 market correction
evolve Cyber Insurance 0.82

// SOC tooling: SIEM -> managed XDR is an accelerating commoditisation
evolve SOC Tooling (SIEM/XDR) 0.85

// Bug bounty platforms (HackerOne/Bugcrowd) continue to productise
evolve Bug Bounty 0.70

// FAIR quantification is slowly moving right but is held back by expert-judgement inertia
evolve FAIR Quantification 0.45 inertia

// Risk matrices are entrenched despite being criticised — inertia
evolve Risk Matrices 0.82 inertia

// LLM-assisted defence is accelerating fast in May 2023 (GPT-4 era)
evolve LLM-Assisted Defence 0.45

// LLM-as-risk is accelerating — regulators (EU AI Act draft, NIST AI RMF Jan 2023) are forcing it onto the register
evolve LLM-as-Risk (prompt injection, data leakage) 0.30
